Speaker A's favorite season is fall due to the mild temperatures and changing colors in nature.
Speaker B enjoys coffee in the morning but also experiments with herbal teas later in the day.
current_dialogue: Speaker A: Did you end up going to the beach or did you stay home on talk on the phone with your grandchildren?
Speaker B: I actually went on a walk to the beach and called my grandchildren there! It's so nice getting to spend time outside, especially in this weather. You must know, since you love to hike!
Speaker A: It is passingly mild for this time of the year. It was only 80 degrees today, and it being nearly August! Do you collect shells when you walk on the beach?
Speaker B: I used to love doing that, but I have to admit its gotten harder as I've gotten older. All that bending up and down is hard n my back!

Speaker A: Hm - I thought you had had a more athletic background. You know, I've been so sedentary my whole life that pains in the back are common - and in the knees, and the hips, and on and on. Camping and fishing is nice, but they don't help strengthen your body

Speaker B: Really? I thought you said you hike and do lots of outdoor activities. Anyway, even though I've been athletic my whole life, its still harder as you get older. You should expect it when you get to my age.

Speaker A: Yea, but that's not the same thing as my siblings who ran for years and years. You know, I disliked them for their athleticism. I ran with them one year - one year almost to the day. Dumbest thing. We weren't going anywhere and, unlike hiking where you can stop and enjoy the surroundings, you just try to zoom past evertyhigng.

Speaker B: That's true... but I guess you get different benefits out of both of them. In hiking, there's beautiful scenery you can absorb. But I think with running, you can feel an almost euphoric high from all those endorphins, so its probably worth it.

Speaker A: Endorphins - ha! If I wanted to get high off some chemicals, I have better ways of going about it than pounding away at the pavement at 7am on a Saturday morning. You know what you should be doing? Sleeping.

Speaker B: That's a weird attitude about endorphins! Maybe if you ever experienced them, you'd realize its way better than sleeping... and maybe then you wouldn't be experiencing so much body pain right now!
e83-s5-t10.response: I suppose there are different ways to find that natural high, whether it's from running or hiking. Maybe I'll give it a try one day and see for myself. But for now, I'll stick to enjoying the changing colors of fall on my upcoming solo hike in Colorado.

Speaker B suggests keeping the baby goats indoors to protect them from hawks.
Speaker B enjoys listening to the sounds of nature and working on the farm with chickens.
Speaker A is expecting their goat to give birth soon.
Speaker B is currently dealing with hawks trying to take their chickens.
current_dialogue: Speaker A: My goat gave birth last night. The scented candles are working great to keep the deer away.
Speaker B: Wow! How many babies did she have? I am glad the candles are working-the Lemon-scented ones work best for me!
Speaker A: She had two! We were excited to get twins!
Speaker B: I bet! Were there any complications with the birth? My neighbor had a goat die during birth :(

Speaker A: That happens more often than I like to think about. Thank God everything went smoothly with our sweet nanny goat. Twin births can be complicated but she is recovering nicely! How are  your chickens?
Speaker B: That's good to hear! The chickens are doing well! We just got an Araucana chicken, and she is beautiful. She has beautiful plumage and lays green eggs!
Speaker A: That is so cool! Chickens are fascinating. Many people don't realize how much variety there is in egg laying! Have you had any more trouble with hawks?

Speaker B: We added a net over the pen so that the chickens can run around freely. There's a ton of variety in egg sizes and shapes. Did you know that you can tell the color of the gg a hen will lay by the pigment of her earlobes?
Speaker A: Hold on, you're telling me chickens have earlobes?? I had no idea! The net is a great idea. That will keep your girls safe!
e110-s5-t9.response: Yes, chickens do have earlobes! It's fascinating how the color of their earlobes can indicate the color of the eggs they lay. The net has been a lifesaver in keeping the hawks away. It's all about finding ways to protect our feathered friends!
